I can see you're trying to search for Google Maps/Timeline exports and SMS backup data, but there are some issues with your PowerShell script. Let me help you fix and improve it:

Fixed PowerShell Script

powershell
# SEARCH FOR GOOGLE MAPS/TIMELINE EXPORTS
Write-Host "`n=== SEARCHING FOR MAPS EXPORT DATA ===" -ForegroundColor Green

Write-Host "Searching for Google Takeout or Maps export files..." -ForegroundColor White
Get-ChildItem -Path C:\Users\User -Recurse -Include "*.json", "*.kml", "*.kmz", "*.csv" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
Where-Object {
    $_.Name -match "(timeline|location|semantic|history|maps|takeout)" -or
    $_.DirectoryName -match "(takeout|google|maps|location)"
} |
Select-Object Name, FullName, LastWriteTime, @{Name="SizeKB";Expression={[math]::Round($_.Length/1KB,2)}}

# CHECK FOR COMMON SMS BACKUP APPLICATIONS
Write-Host "`n=== CHECKING FOR SMS BACKUP APPLICATIONS ===" -ForegroundColor Green

$smsBackupApps = @(
    "SMS Backup",
    "Super Backup",
    "Backup Your Mobile",
    "Google Drive",
    "Samsung Cloud"
)

foreach ($app in $smsBackupApps) {
    Write-Host "Searching for: $app" -ForegroundColor White
    Get-ChildItem -Path C:\Users\User -Recurse -Include "*.xml", "*.json", "*.db", "*.csv" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
    Where-Object { 
        $_.Name -match $app -or 
        $_.DirectoryName -match $app -or
        (Get-Content $_.FullName -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-String $app -Quiet)
    } |
    Select-Object Name, FullName, @{Name="SizeKB";Expression={[math]::Round($_.Length/1KB,2)}}
}

# QUICK SMS DATA STATUS
Write-Host "`n=== SMS DATA RECOVERY STATUS ===" -ForegroundColor Cyan

Write-Host "To recover SMS messages from April-May 2021:" -ForegroundColor White
Write-Host "1. Check your phone's messaging app directly" -ForegroundColor Yellow
Write-Host "2. Look for Google Messages web: https://messages.google.com/web" -ForegroundColor Yellow

Additional Search Options

If you want to search more broadly for potential SMS/message data:

powershell
# BROADER SEARCH FOR MESSAGE DATA
Write-Host "`n=== SEARCHING FOR MESSAGE/COMMUNICATION DATA ===" -ForegroundColor Green

$messagePatterns = @("sms", "message", "text", "backup", "conversation", "chat")

foreach ($pattern in $messagePatterns) {
    Write-Host "Searching for files containing: $pattern" -ForegroundColor White
    Get-ChildItem -Path C:\Users\User -Recurse -Include "*.xml", "*.json", "*.db", "*.csv", "*.txt" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
    Where-Object { 
        $_.Name -match $pattern -or
        (Get-Content $_.FullName -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue | Select-String $pattern -Quiet)
    } |
    Select-Object Name, FullName, LastWriteTime, @{Name="SizeKB";Expression={[math]::Round($_.Length/1KB,2)}} |
    Format-Table -AutoSize
}

Key Fixes Made:

  1. Removed -Raw parameter - This parameter doesn't exist in older PowerShell versions

  2. Used Select-String - More reliable for content searching

  3. Added error handling - For file content reading

  4. Expanded file types - Added .db and .txt for SMS backups

  5. Better pattern matching - For directory names and file content

Alternative SMS Recovery Methods:

Since the automated search might not find everything, consider these manual approaches:

  1. Check cloud services directly:

    • Google Drive (look for backup folders)

    • Samsung Cloud (if you have a Samsung device)

    • iCloud (if you use iPhone)

  2. Phone-specific options:

    • Android: Settings > Google > Backup

    • iPhone: Settings > [Your Name] > iCloud > Manage Storage > Backups

  3. Third-party apps: Check if you have apps like:

    • SMS Backup & Restore

    • Super Backup & Restore

    • My Backup Pro

The files you found (like CROSS_PLATFORM_TIMELINE.csv) might contain some relevant data, so examine those closely for any message-related information.

powershell
# FOCUSED SEARCH FOR APRIL 30 - MAY 5, 2021
Write-Host "`n=== FOCUSED SEARCH: APRIL 30 - MAY 5, 2021 ===" -ForegroundColor Red -BackgroundColor White

Write-Host "Searching specifically for files from April 30 to May 5, 2021..." -ForegroundColor Yellow

# Search for documents with specific date patterns
$datePatterns = @(
    "2021-04-30", "04/30/2021", "30/04/2021", "April 30, 2021",
    "2021-05-01", "05/01/2021", "01/05/2021", "May 1, 2021", 
    "2021-05-02", "05/02/2021", "02/05/2021", "May 2, 2021",
    "2021-05-03", "05/03/2021", "03/05/2021", "May 3, 2021",
    "2021-05-04", "05/04/2021", "04/05/2021", "May 4, 2021",
    "2021-05-05", "05/05/2021", "05/05/2021", "May 5, 2021"
)

# Search in document files
$documentFiles = Get-ChildItem -Path C:\Users\User -Recurse -Include "*.doc", "*.docx", "*.pdf", "*.txt", "*.rtf" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

foreach ($file in $documentFiles) {
    try {
        $content = Get-Content $file.FullName -Raw -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
        if ($content) {
            foreach ($pattern in $datePatterns) {
                if ($content -match $pattern) {
                    Write-Host "FOUND DATE: $pattern in $($file.Name)" -ForegroundColor Green
                    Write-Host "File: $($file.FullName)" -ForegroundColor White
                    Write-Host "Last Modified: $($file.LastWriteTime)" -ForegroundColor Yellow
                    break
                }
            }
        }
    } catch {
        # Skip files that can't be read
    }
}

powershell
# EXTRACT THE SCREENSHOT ARCHIVE - THIS IS YOUR BEST BET!
Write-Host "`n=== EXTRACTING SCREENSHOT ARCHIVE NOW ===" -ForegroundColor Red -BackgroundColor White

$zipPath = "C:\Users\User\Downloads\relauratextscreenshots.zip"
$extractPath = "C:\Users\User\Downloads\extracted_text_screenshots"

if (Test-Path $zipPath) {
    Write-Host "FOUND SCREENSHOT ARCHIVE: $zipPath" -ForegroundColor Green
    Write-Host "Size: $([math]::Round((Get-Item $zipPath).Length/1MB,2)) MB" -ForegroundColor Yellow
    
    try {
        # Create extraction directory
        if (!(Test-Path $extractPath)) {
            New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path $extractPath -Force
        }
        
        Write-Host "Extracting to: $extractPath" -ForegroundColor White
        Expand-Archive -Path $zipPath -DestinationPath $extractPath -Force
        Write-Host "EXTRACTION SUCCESSFUL!" -ForegroundColor Green
        
        # Show what was extracted
        Write-Host "`n=== EXTRACTED FILES ===" -ForegroundColor Cyan
        $extractedFiles = Get-ChildItem -Path $extractPath -Recurse -Include "*.jpg", "*.png", "*.jpeg", "*.txt", "*.pdf" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
        if ($extractedFiles) {
            $extractedFiles | Select-Object Name, FullName, @{Name="SizeKB";Expression={[math]::Round($_.Length/1KB,2)}}
            
            Write-Host "`nOPENING EXTRACTED FOLDER..." -ForegroundColor Yellow
            Start-Process explorer.exe $extractPath
        } else {
            Write-Host "No image files found in archive" -ForegroundColor Red
        }
        
    } catch {
        Write-Host "Extraction failed: $($_.Exception.Message)" -ForegroundColor Red
    }
} else {
    Write-Host "ZIP file not found at: $zipPath" -ForegroundColor Red
}

SEARCH FOR SPECIFIC POOL QUOTE FILES

powershell
# SEARCH FOR POOL QUOTE DOCUMENTS SPECIFICALLY
Write-Host "`n=== SEARCHING FOR POOL QUOTE DOCUMENTS ===" -ForegroundColor Green

$searchLocations = @(
    "$env:USERPROFILE\Downloads",
    "$env:USERPROFILE\Documents", 
    "$env:USERPROFILE\Desktop",
    "$env:USERPROFILE\OneDrive"
)

$poolKeywords = @("pool", "quote", "estimate", "proposal", "contract", "construction", "swimming")

foreach ($location in $searchLocations) {
    if (Test-Path $location) {
        Write-Host "`nSearching in: $location" -ForegroundColor Cyan
        foreach ($keyword in $poolKeywords) {
            Get-ChildItem -Path $location -Recurse -Include "*.pdf", "*.doc", "*.docx", "*.odt", "*.txt" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
            Where-Object { $_.Name -match $keyword } |
            Select-Object Name, FullName, LastWriteTime, @{Name="SizeKB";Expression={[math]::Round($_.Length/1KB,2)}}
        }
    }
}

    "*Timeline*",
    "*google*maps*",
    "*My Activity*"

    Get-ChildItem -Path C:\Users\User -Recurse -Include "*$pattern*" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue |
    Where-Object { $_.Length -gt 1000 } |  # Only files larger than 1KB

CHECK FOR GOOGLE TAKEOUT ZIP FILES

powershell
# SEARCH FOR GOOGLE TAKEOUT ZIP ARCHIVES
Write-Host "`n=== SEARCHING FOR GOOGLE TAKEOUT ARCHIVES ===" -ForegroundColor Magenta

$takeoutZips = Get-ChildItem -Path C:\Users\User -Recurse -Include "takeout*.zip", "google*takeout*.zip" -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

if ($takeoutZips) {
    Write-Host "FOUND GOOGLE TAKEOUT ARCHIVES:" -ForegroundColor Green
    $takeoutZips | Select-Object Name, FullName, LastWriteTime, @{Name="SizeMB";Expression={[math]::Round($_.Length/1MB,2)}}
    
    # Check what's inside the Takeout archives
    foreach ($zip in $takeoutZips) {
        Write-Host "`nContents of $($zip.Name):" -ForegroundColor Cyan
        try {
            Add-Type -AssemblyName System.IO.Compression.FileSystem
            $archive = [System.IO.Compression.ZipFile]::OpenRead($zip.FullName)
            $locationFiles = $archive.Entries | Where-Object { $_.FullName -match "Location|Timeline|Maps" }
            if ($locationFiles) {
                Write-Host "Location-related files found:" -ForegroundColor Green
                $locationFiles | Select-Object Name, @{Name="SizeMB";Expression={[math]::Round($_.Length/1MB,2)}}
            }
            $archive.Dispose()
        } catch {
            Write-Host "Could not read archive contents" -ForegroundColor Red
        }
    }
} else {
    Write-Host "No Google Takeout archives found" -ForegroundColor Yellow
}
